##It's not just the pavilions. What's going on down there

Interview | reporter of China Youth Daily, Zheng Li, correspondent, Wang Yong, Xiongying Chen

By Qu Junyan

February 9, after several days of rain in Wuhan finally cleared up, Baibu Pavilion Community residents go out to buy vegetables and medicine, there are people jogging around the garden. If you ignore the masks on people's faces, everything looks as calm as any Sunday on a calendar. On the same day, Wuhan launched a "total offensive" to control the outbreak of NCP, a community of one hundred thousand people that had been asked to, "Four categories of people" , including confirmed patients, suspected patients, patients with fever and close contacts, were treated and isolated accordingly.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A medical worker talks to family members inside the Zhenhua building, the Party School of the Hubei Provincial Party Committee, on Feb. 9. This is a centralized quarantine site for suspected new coronavirus patients. In order to avoid infecting family members, medical staff will be housed in a centralized quarantine site. After the outbreak has been lifted, there will still be 14 days of quarantine. Photograph by Wang Jiaxing

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
February 8, Wuhan Baibu Pavilion Community Three Neighborhood Committee, staff by telephone to verify the "four categories of people" in the community information and situation. Photo by Zheng Li

This is a war without guns. The "enemy" is an invisible COVID-19, fought by every person who breathes it. Outside the "main battlefield" hospital, the grass-roots communities and villages become the first line of joint prevention and control of the epidemic, participate in on-duty or home isolation, everyone is deeply aware of the urgency of the campaign.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Residents walk past a pharmacy on a street in Wuhan's Baibu Pavilion Community on Feb. 9. Photo by Zheng Li

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A resident wears a raincoat to protect himself on a street in Wuhan's Baibu Pavilion Community on Feb. 9. Photo by Zheng Li

The villages of Henan were given the image of "hard core" in the epidemic prevention battle: Village cadres armed to the teeth set up retreats at the entrance of the village, and loudspeakers circulated epidemic prevention notices in Henan dialects, even the selection of Henan Opera is adapted into Epidemic Prevention "Shun Kou Liu" ... as the country's largest population province, the southern part of Henan and the border of Hubei in the "hard core" behind, more realistic considerations.

"Our job is: no one from this village leaves the village, no one from outside the village enters the village, " said Chen Song, Secretary of the Party branch in Zulou village, Liuhe Town, Henan Province. In the old people's home of Liuhe Town, an old man of nearly 70 disinfected the whole hospital three times a day for nearly an hour. The Dean and the administrator of the home for the aged take the temperature and register the record every morning and evening. The young Liu he town Censorou Village Party Branch Secretary 1 Kings involved in epidemic prevention so far, has not returned home for nearly a month, his child is only 8 months old.

Workers disinfect villagers'homes in the town of Liuhe in Yongcheng, Henan Province on Feb. 5. Photograph by Wang Yong

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A worker takes a temperature at a nursing home for the elderly in Liuhe Township, Yongcheng, Henan Province, Feb. 5,2010. Photograph by Wang Yong

Not Far Away in Sunchang Village, Party branch Secretary Dou Yuling went door to door with a small loudspeaker until her voice cracked. Her husband, Sun Jiashun, is the village doctor in Sunchang village, responsible for explaining the knowledge of epidemic prevention and control for the whole village, disinfection of public areas. The oldest son works 24-hour shifts at a checkpoint, and the second son works at a fever clinic. All four members of the family are holding on to their posts in the front line of the fight against the epidemic. This Spring Festival is especially special for them.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Sun Chang village, Liuhe Town, Yongcheng, Henan Province, on February 5,2010. Photograph by Wang Yong

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On February 5, workers in Yanshoucun village, Huangkou town, Yongcheng, Henan Province, took measures to register, measure temperature and disinfect people who had gone out to the village. Photograph by Wang Yong

In the town of Guo Wa village, the villagers every day coincidentally to the cadres on duty to send food, to express gratitude. Guo Wa village doctor Li Hua calls home every day to return to his hometown in Wuhan and to return to his hometown via Hubei. In Zulou village, Wu Xia, who returned home from Changsha via Wuhan on January 13, volunteered to stay in isolation for 14 days. "Now 14 days later, I will not run around, just waiting for the end of the day, we will pack up and go out to make money. "

Villagers dig wild vegetables in their wheat fields in the village of Ni Ge, in the town of Liuhe, Henan Province, on Feb. 9. Photograph by Wang Yong

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Reuters / Bobby Yip villagers return to their village in the town of Liuhe, Yongcheng, Henan Province February 5,2010. Photograph by Wang Yong

Zixing, more than 600 kilometers from Wuhan, is a county-level city in Hunan Province with a population of less than 400,000. As at 2400 hours on 11 February, a total of four new cases of pneumonia had been confirmed in Zixing. The number of confirmed cases is not large, but the city is still on high alert to deal with it: from January 25 to 30, all agricultural markets in the city will be closed and disinfected, focusing on areas such as live poultry and meat; from January 29, people from outside the city will be banned from entering, residents are required to have their temperature taken when they return from outside the city, and on 7 February, closed management of villages and communities began.

Before and after the winter solstice last year, when not affected by the outbreak, Chennan village in Zixing's Sandu town also held a lively "pig-killing Rice" feast, attracting more than 400 tourists and villagers. This is the local winter solstice to the year before the custom, a symbol of abundant labor and friendship. Today, the village is quiet everywhere, there is no personnel exchanges, New Year's greetings in the telephone and Wechat. The contrast is not just in Zichen, where villages across the country have been restrained by the epidemic.

For the first time, many people joke that lying down at home can contribute to society. As the "last kilometer" of the epidemic prevention system, community and rural governance is faced with a delicate and complicated task, which requires everyone's patience and self-consciousness. By the time the epidemic is over, we expect to be greeted not only with fresh air but also with a sense of national health and safety that has been built up in the months of solidarity.
